    <h1>Day 47 Lab</h1>
    <h2 class="lab-card">Azure Core Services: Deploying Compute, Networking, and Storage</h2>
  </header>

  <main>
    <div class="lab-card">
      <p><strong>Objective:</strong> Gain hands-on experience with Azureâ€™s core services by deploying a virtual machine, creating a virtual network, and attaching a storage account.</p>

      <h3>ðŸ›  Tools Needed:</h3>
      <ul>
        <li>Azure free account: <a href="https://azure.microsoft.com/free" target="_blank">azure.microsoft.com/free</a></li>
        <li>Web browser (Chrome or Edge)</li>
      </ul>

      <h3>Step 1: Set Up a Virtual Network (VNet)</h3>
      <ul>
        <li>In the Azure Portal, search for <strong>Virtual networks</strong> and click <strong>Create</strong></li>
        <li>Use these settings:
          <ul>
            <li><strong>Resource group:</strong> RG-AzureBasics</li>
            <li><strong>Name:</strong> <code>VNet-Lab</code></li>
            <li><strong>Region:</strong> Same as previous lab</li>
          </ul>
        </li>
        <li>Leave address space and subnets as default</li>
        <li>Click <strong>Review + Create</strong> â†’ <strong>Create</strong></li>
      </ul>

      <h3>Step 2: Deploy a Virtual Machine</h3>
      <ul>
        <li>Search for <strong>Virtual Machines</strong> and click <strong>Create</strong></li>
        <li>Configure the basics:
          <ul>
            <li><strong>Resource group:</strong> RG-AzureBasics</li>
            <li><strong>VM name:</strong> <code>MyLabVM</code></li>
            <li><strong>Region:</strong> Same as VNet</li>
            <li><strong>Image:</strong> Ubuntu 20.04 LTS</li>
            <li><strong>Size:</strong> Use the smallest free-tier-eligible VM</li>
            <li><strong>Username:</strong> anything (e.g., <code>azuser</code>)</li>
            <li><strong>Authentication:</strong> Password</li>
          </ul>
        </li>
        <li>Under <strong>Networking</strong>, select <code>VNet-Lab</code> and default subnet</li>
        <li>Click through to <strong>Review + Create</strong> â†’ then <strong>Create</strong></li>
      </ul>

      <h3>Step 3: Access the VM</h3>
      <ul>
        <li>Once the VM is created, go to its overview page</li>
        <li>Copy the public IP address</li>
        <li>Open a terminal and connect using SSH:
          <pre><code>ssh azuser@&lt;your-ip&gt;</code></pre>
        </li>
        <li>Accept the fingerprint and log in with your password</li>
        <li>Run: <code>uname -a</code> to verify itâ€™s a Linux machine</li>
      </ul>

      <h3>Step 4: Create a Storage Account</h3>
      <ul>
        <li>Search for <strong>Storage accounts</strong> and click <strong>Create</strong></li>
        <li>Fill in:
          <ul>
            <li><strong>Resource group:</strong> RG-AzureBasics</li>
            <li><strong>Storage account name:</strong> something unique like <code>labstorage47</code></li>
            <li><strong>Region:</strong> Same as VM</li>
          </ul>
        </li>
        <li>Click <strong>Review + Create</strong> â†’ <strong>Create</strong></li>
        <li>After deployment, explore the storage account â†’ Containers â†’ Create a container named <code>labfiles</code></li>
        <li>Upload a small text file or screenshot</li>
      </ul>

      <h3>Step 5: Clean Up (Optional)</h3>
      <ul>
        <li>Go to <strong>Resource Groups</strong> â†’ <code>RG-AzureBasics</code></li>
        <li>Click <strong>Delete resource group</strong> if you want to avoid charges</li>
      </ul>

      <hr />
      <p><strong>Lab Summary:</strong> You deployed core cloud infrastructure: a virtual network, a Linux VM, and a storage account. This is the foundation of most real-world Azure environments. In future labs, you'll build on these with identity, security, and monitoring tools.</p>
    </div>
